@NODE #modes "SingleFile and MultiFile modes"
	What diffirences are between Single and MultiFile modes?

	As you propably noticed Image Descriptor allows you to select
	more than one file to load. But it is impossible to load all 
	files into memory when you have ie. 300 files selected.

	Instead of this Image Descriptor just "remembers" all selected
	filenames together with their directory. Now when you press
	the Save button (or CleanUp) Image Descriptor will process
	all files one by one. 

	The consequnce of this is that no file is in memory and you 
	are unable to view this image or its description or some image 
	info.

	Becouse Image Descriptor supports four image types also 
	a problem with description types appears.

	To avoid this you need to specify which image type should
	be used. 

	This is required becouse GIF and JPEG images can hold only
	a simple comment while ILBM images use much detailed
	description (author, title, copyrights) and PNG images
	can hold even more. 

	This is so called MultiFile mode.

	
	Since Image Description 2.3 a new MultiFile mode was been
	introduced.

	The new enhanced mode allows you to view image or view image
	info. 

	Also a HTML list of files can be created if you wish.

	To make this things work the program must scan each selected
	file to make sure that this is image. For large directories
	on rather slow devices (like old CD-ROMs) this can take a 
	while.

	
	In Image Descriptor 2.4 few things are fixed or reworked.

	You can now disable file scanning if you wish and all options
	in new MultiFile are still available but you dont need to wait
	anymore.

	Note, that if you disable file scanning the file list will
	show "???" as the image type and the HTML index will contain
	only filenames.


	The SingleFile mode is typical situation when only one file
	was been selected. This file is loaded into memory and its
	there until another file(s) is selected or a load operation
	is canceled by user or by some error(s).


	To enable MultiFile mode you need to select at least two files.

	To return to SingleFile mode you need to select only one file.

@ENDNODE
@NODE #thumb "Thumbnail support"
	Image Descriptor 2.4 supports following JPEG thumbnail types:

	- Adobe Photoshop thumbnail
	- Embedded thumbnail
	- JFXX: JPEG thumbnail
	- JFXX: True color thumbnail 

	JFXX: greyscaled or 8bit paletted thumbnails are currently not
	supported.
	
	If you have slow computer the thumbnails are excellent solution
	for you. It is much faster to show 80x60 pixels image instead
	of 800X600.

	There are many programs which can create thumbnails but i think
	it is useful only for JPEG images as decompression of such image
	can sometimes take long time.

	I recommend my small tool called CreateThumbNail which can
	create jpeg thumbnails (JFXX) very fast and easy.

	Aminet: gfx/misc/ctn.lha

	
@ENDNODE
@NODE #bugs "Known bugs / problems"
	@{B}Known bugs / problems
	---------------------@{UB}

	H@{U}m@{UU}m.. @{I}What@{UI} did you say? a bu@{B}g@{UB}?? wh.re?@{U}?@{UU}?

	Here you can find informations about known bugs or problems
	which may (or not) appear.

	@{B}1. First, i must warning you about 2 Mungwall hits that may
	appear while Image Descriptor is starting.@{UB}

	I dont know exactly where is the problem, but i`ve discover
	that these hits appear when program executes:

	MUIM_Application_Load

	This is MUI method which in short loads ID2`s settings.
	(In fact it only load gadget contents/states)

	I`ve also discover that MUI Builder makes exactly the same
	Mungwall hits during start, so i think that the problem
	is in code generated by MUI Builder.(but i`m not sure !)

	The good news is that these hits are absolutely harmless.
	(allocating zero bytes of memory is illegal but harmless)

	Hold on your pants ! Investigation in progress ...

@ENDNODE
